version: 1
title: "speckle v0.1.0"
notes: |
  Speckle self-spec. Title tracks the next planned release version.
  Convention: run /speckle before implementing each new feature or release.
  Agent proposes spec sections; human approves via browser; then implement.
dimensions:
  - id: cli
    label: CLI
    color: "#4A90D9"
  - id: format
    label: Format
    color: "#E67E22"
  - id: history
    label: History
    color: "#27AE60"
  - id: llm
    label: LLM
    color: "#9B59B6"
sections:
  - id: versioning
    heading: Version tracking in spec
    dimension: format
    body: |
      The spec format has `version` (format schema version) but no field for
      the product version the spec is planning. How should we track which
      product release a spec covers?
    decisions:
      - id: product_version_field
        prompt: How to embed product version in the spec
        options:
          - id: title_convention
            label: "Title convention — embed version in the title (current approach)"
            selected: true
          - id: new_field
            label: "New field — add top-level product_version: \"0.1.0\" to the spec format"
          - id: omit
            label: "Omit — version tracked only in git tags, not the spec"
            selected: false
        comment: "title_convention — embed version in the title"
  - id: scaffolding
    heading: "speckle new — scaffold command"
    dimension: cli
    body: |
      New users must write specs from scratch. A scaffold command would reduce
      friction and promote good spec structure.
    decisions:
      - id: new_command
        prompt: "Add `speckle new <file.speckle>`"
        options:
          - id: yes
            label: "Yes — generate a commented starter spec with example sections and decisions"
            selected: true
          - id: no
            label: "No — examples in README are sufficient"
        comment: "yes — add speckle new <file.speckle>"
  - id: validation
    heading: "speckle validate — CI pre-flight"
    dimension: cli
    body: |
      Parse errors currently surface only when `speckle serve` runs.
      A validate command enables CI pipelines to catch broken specs before serve.
    decisions:
      - id: validate_command
        prompt: "Add `speckle validate <file.speckle>`"
        options:
          - id: yes_exit_code
            label: "Yes — exit 0/1, print errors to stderr (shell-friendly)"
            selected: false
          - id: yes_json
            label: "Yes — output structured JSON errors (tooling-friendly)"
            selected: true
          - id: no
            label: "No — serve validates on startup; separate command is redundant"
        comment: "yes_json — keep v0.2.0 JSON output. Round 3 yes_exit_code was misclick."
  - id: history_cli
    heading: History navigation commands
    dimension: history
    body: |
      The history repo holds full decision history but requires raw git commands
      to inspect. CLI helpers make the audit trail accessible without git knowledge.
    decisions:
      - id: log_command
        prompt: "Add `speckle log <file.speckle>`"
        options:
          - id: yes
            label: "Yes — list past rounds: timestamp, message, decision summary"
            selected: true
          - id: no
            label: "No — git log in .speckle-repo is sufficient"
        comment: "yes — add speckle log"
      - id: show_command
        prompt: "Add `speckle show <file.speckle> <ref>`"
        options:
          - id: yes
            label: "Yes — print spec + decisions for a given commit ref"
            selected: true
          - id: no
            label: "No — git show in .speckle-repo is sufficient"
        comment: "yes — add speckle show <ref>"
  - id: self_spec_process
    heading: Self-spec conventions
    dimension: format
    body: |
      Conventions for how speckle uses itself to plan its own development.
    decisions:
      - id: spec_granularity
        prompt: When to run a self-spec round
        options:
          - id: per_feature
            label: "Per feature — spec each feature before implementing it"
            selected: false
          - id: per_release
            label: "Per release — spec the full release before any implementation"
          - id: hybrid
            label: "Hybrid — release-level spec first, then per-feature rounds for detail"
            selected: true
        comment: "hybrid — release-level spec first, then per-feature rounds for detail"
      - id: proposal_ownership
        prompt: Who proposes spec changes
        options:
          - id: agent_proposes
            label: "Agent proposes — agent drafts spec sections, human reviews via /speckle"
          - id: human_proposes
            label: "Human proposes — human edits .speckle directly, agent serves and awaits"
          - id: both
            label: "Both — either party may propose; /speckle is the gate regardless"
            selected: true
        comment: "both — either party may propose; /speckle is the gate"
  - id: spec_codes
    heading: Spec codes — identifiers for dimensions and decisions
    dimension: format
    body: |
      Each dimension and decision currently has a free-form id. Structured codes
      (e.g. UX-001, ENG-003) would make specs referenceable in commit messages,
      PRs, and changelogs. Codes could be auto-assigned or manually set.
    decisions:
      - id: code_format
        prompt: Code format
        options:
          - id: dim_seq
            label: "DIM-NNN — dimension prefix + zero-padded sequence (e.g. UX-001)"
            selected: true
          - id: free
            label: "Free-form — keep current id strings, no enforced format"
          - id: uuid
            label: "UUID — stable opaque codes, no human meaning"
        comment: "dim_seq — DIM-NNN prefix + sequence"
      - id: code_assignment
        prompt: How codes are assigned
        options:
          - id: auto
            label: "Auto — speckle assigns next available code on patch/commit"
            selected: true
          - id: manual
            label: "Manual — author sets code field in YAML; speckle validates uniqueness"
          - id: both
            label: "Both — auto-assign if omitted, allow manual override"
        comment: "auto — speckle assigns; humans only interact via CLI or Speckler UI"
      - id: code_scope
        prompt: What gets a code
        options:
          - id: decisions_only
            label: "Decisions only — each decision gets a code; dimensions use their id"
          - id: sections_and_decisions
            label: "Sections + decisions — both get codes"
          - id: everything
            label: "Everything — dimensions, sections, decisions, and options all get codes"
            selected: true
        comment: "everything — dimensions, sections, decisions, options all get codes"
  - id: spec_inbox
    heading: Spec inbox — per-dimension idea queue with LLM integration
    dimension: llm
    body: |
      An inbox lets users drop raw ideas into a dimension without structuring them
      as decisions. Speckle pipes the inbox text plus the current spec to an LLM,
      which proposes new sections/decisions or updates existing ones. The agent
      reviews the proposal and patches the spec.
    decisions:
      - id: inbox_location
        prompt: Where the inbox lives
        options:
          - id: in_spec
            label: "In spec — top-level inbox: field per dimension in the YAML"
            selected: true
          - id: sidecar
            label: "Sidecar — separate <spec>.inbox.yaml file, not committed to history"
          - id: stdin
            label: "stdin — user pipes ideas via `speckle inbox <file> <dim-id>`"
        comment: "in_spec + stdin — top-level inbox field per dimension; also support stdin pipe"
      - id: llm_integration
        prompt: How speckle calls the LLM
        options:
          - id: subprocess
            label: "Subprocess — configurable command in .speckle-manifest.json; speckle pipes context to stdin, reads overlay from stdout"
            selected: false
          - id: api_key
            label: "Built-in API — speckle calls Anthropic/OpenAI directly via env var key"
          - id: agent_only
            label: "Agent-mediated — speckle emits a prompt on stdout; the calling agent runs the LLM and pipes the result back"
            selected: true
        comment: "agent_only — inbox in await JSON; calling agent handles LLM call. Round 3 subprocess was misclick."
      - id: inbox_trigger
        prompt: When inbox processing runs
        options:
          - id: on_serve
            label: "On serve — process inbox automatically before starting the server"
          - id: explicit
            label: "Explicit — `speckle process-inbox <file>` command; user decides when"
            selected: true
          - id: on_submit
            label: "On submit — process inbox after human submits decisions in browser"
            selected: true
        comment: "both explicit and on_submit"
      - id: inbox_output
        prompt: What the LLM produces
        options:
          - id: overlay
            label: "YAML overlay — same format as speckle patch input; agent applies it"
            selected: true
          - id: new_sections
            label: "New sections only — LLM appends sections; never modifies existing ones"
          - id: full_rewrite
            label: "Full spec rewrite — LLM rewrites the entire spec; human reviews diff"
        comment: "overlay — YAML overlay format, agent applies via speckle patch"
  - id: speckler_ui
    heading: "Speckler — browser UI identity and CLI parity"
    dimension: format
    body: |
      The browser UI shall be called "Speckler". The goal is idiomatic parity:
      everything visible in Speckler has a CLI equivalent and vice versa.
      Three interaction modes exist in the UI (see spec_modes section).
    decisions:
      - id: ui_name
        prompt: Official name for the browser UI
        options:
          - id: speckler
            label: "Speckler — distinct name from the CLI tool (speckle)"
          - id: speckle_ui
            label: "Speckle UI — same name, qualified"
            selected: true
        comment: "speckle_ui — 'Speckle UI', same name qualified"
      - id: cli_parity
        prompt: CLI parity scope
        options:
          - id: full
            label: "Full — every Speckler action has a CLI command equivalent"
            selected: true
          - id: partial
            label: "Partial — CLI covers automation paths; Speckler covers interactive paths"
        comment: "full — every Speckler action has a CLI equivalent"
  - id: spec_modes
    heading: "Speckler — three UI interaction modes"
    dimension: format
    body: |
      The Speckler UI has three distinct interaction zones with different edit modes:
      1. Requirements inbox — raw ideas, entered by user or LLM, edit-first
      2. Current specifications — settled decisions, read-first (can alter with intent)
      3. New decisions — pending decisions awaiting human input, edit-first
      This maps directly to the spec YAML: inbox field, decided sections, open sections.
    decisions:
      - id: mode_transitions
        prompt: How modes are presented in the UI
        options:
          - id: tabs
            label: "Tabs — three tabs at top: Inbox / Specs / Decisions"
          - id: sections
            label: "Inline sections — all three zones visible in one scrollable page, visually distinct"
          - id: sidebar
            label: "Sidebar — mode selector on left, content area on right"
            selected: true
        comment: "sidebar — mode selector on left, content area on right"
      - id: settled_edit_guard
        prompt: How to guard editing settled specifications
        options:
          - id: click_to_edit
            label: "Click to edit — settled specs show a lock icon; single click unlocks for edit"
            selected: true
          - id: explicit_reopen
            label: "Explicit reopen — user must run speckle reopen <decision-id> to unseal"
          - id: free_edit
            label: "Free edit — no guard; history shows what changed"
        comment: "click_to_edit — lock icon; single click unlocks"
  - id: history_ui
    heading: "Speckler — version history toolbar"
    dimension: history
    body: |
      The browser shows a top toolbar with version history. Selecting an older version
      shows a read-only view of that spec snapshot. A [Current] button snaps back to
      the live version. Each version has a timestamp and a short digest summarising
      what changed. The digest is written by the agent at commit time.
      This requires a source-of-truth state machine to model correctly.
    decisions:
      - id: version_digest_author
        prompt: Who writes the version digest
        options:
          - id: agent
            label: "Agent — included in speckle commit --digest flag; agent generates from decisions diff"
            selected: true
          - id: human
            label: "Human — free-text field in the commit message; agent prompts but human edits"
          - id: auto
            label: "Auto-generated — speckle diffs the spec and generates a summary without LLM"
        comment: "agent — speckle commit --digest flag; agent generates from decisions diff"
      - id: history_state_machine
        prompt: State machine for spec versions
        options:
          - id: linear
            label: "Linear — versions are a single sequence; no branching"
            selected: true
          - id: branching
            label: "Branching — versions can fork (one spec, multiple decision paths)"
          - id: linear_with_rebase
            label: "Linear with rebase — linear by default; explicit rebase allowed"
        comment: "linear — single sequence, no branching"
      - id: readonly_nav
        prompt: Read-only view of past versions
        options:
          - id: inline_toolbar
            label: "Inline toolbar — version picker in top bar of Speckler, same page"
          - id: separate_url
            label: "Separate URL — /history/<ref> route; [Current] links back to /"
            selected: true
        comment: "separate_url — /history/<ref> route; [Current] links back to /"
  - id: option_generation
    heading: "Option quality — pros/cons, recommendations, and LLM variants"
    dimension: llm
    body: |
      When speckle (via the agent) proposes options, it should:
      - Supply pros and cons for each option
      - Recommend one option based on product and engineering fit
      - Offer an "Add different option" affordance that triggers the LLM to generate
        alternatives using a mode selector: hybrid / adjacent / experimental / mix
      These require new fields in the spec format and new rendering in Speckler.
    decisions:
      - id: pros_cons_format
        prompt: How pros/cons are stored in the spec
        options:
          - id: option_fields
            label: "Fields on option — pros: [list] and cons: [list] fields in the option YAML"
            selected: true
          - id: decision_field
            label: "Field on decision — tradeoffs: markdown block summarising all options"
          - id: body_convention
            label: "Convention only — agent writes pros/cons in the option label or body; no schema change"
        comment: "option_fields — pros: [list] and cons: [list] on each option"
      - id: recommendation_field
        prompt: How the recommended option is marked
        options:
          - id: flag_field
            label: "recommended: true field on the option"
            selected: true
          - id: decision_field
            label: "recommended: <option-id> field on the decision"
          - id: comment_convention
            label: "Convention — agent notes recommendation in the decision comment"
        comment: "flag_field — recommended: true on the option"
      - id: add_different_trigger
        prompt: How "Add different option" works
        options:
          - id: inline_button
            label: "Speckler button — sends mode + context to agent via inbox; agent patches spec"
          - id: cli_command
            label: "CLI — speckle expand <decision-id> --mode hybrid/adjacent/experimental/mix"
          - id: both
            label: "Both — Speckler button triggers CLI equivalent under the hood"
            selected: true
        comment: "both — Speckler button + speckle expand CLI command"
  - id: comment_lifecycle
    heading: Comment lifecycle — ingest and clear
    dimension: llm
    body: |
      Comments on decisions (the comment: field) capture human intent at decision time.
      They should guide the agent's next revision. Once the agent has ingested a round
      and patched the spec, comments on decided options should be cleared so they
      do not pollute future rounds.
    decisions:
      - id: comment_clear_timing
        prompt: When to clear comments
        options:
          - id: on_patch
            label: "On patch — speckle patch clears comment fields for all decided options"
            selected: true
          - id: on_next_serve
            label: "On next serve — comments persist in YAML but hidden in Speckler after ingestion"
          - id: never_auto
            label: "Never auto-clear — agent explicitly deletes comments in the overlay"
        comment: "on_patch — speckle patch clears comment fields for decided options"
      - id: comment_preservation
        prompt: Where cleared comments go
        options:
          - id: history_only
            label: "History only — live in .speckle-repo commit body; cleared from spec file"
            selected: true
          - id: archive_field
            label: "Archive field — moved to archived_comment: on the option (hidden in UI)"
          - id: discard
            label: "Discard — not preserved after patch; history commit has the record"
        comment: "history_only — cleared from spec file; preserved in .speckle-repo commit"
